                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d416">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/7468: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-30T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >November 30, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>64. Nanking’s 114, November 28, 5 p.m., first paragraph. The Chinese Ambassador
                    called yesterday on the Secretary and communicated information with regard to
                    recent developments in the North China situation.</p>
                <p>The substance of the comment made by the Secretary to the Ambassador was that
                    this Government was watching the situation closely <pb facs="0569" n="457"
                        xml:id="pg_457"/> and carefully considering the question of the course which
                    it should take.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Tokyo as Department’s No. 187.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
